 16. Details of 2 Phase Commit
 =============================================================
 -> Two-Phase Commit (2PC) is a distributed transaction protocol used to ensure atomicity (all-or-nothing) across multiple services or databases.
    . Prepare stage
    . Commit stage
    
 ->  Why do we need 2PC?
    . In a distributed system, a single transaction may span multiple services or databases.
      
     Example Problem (Without 2PC)
     
           Order Service saves order ✅
           Payment Service deducts money ✅
           Inventory Service fails ❌

           ➡️ System becomes inconsistent
           
         2PC solves this problem
         
         👥 Main Components

              Coordinator (Transaction Manager)
                   Controls the transaction
                   Decides commit or rollback
              Participants (Resource Managers)
                   Databases / microservices
                   Follow coordinator’s instructions
                   
       ✅ Phase 1: Prepare Phase (Voting Phase)

                 Coordinator asks all participants:
                 "Can you commit?"
                 
       ✅ Phase 2: Commit Phase
                   Case 1: All say YES
                             Coordinator sends COMMIT
                             Participants commit changes
                             Release locks

                   Case 2: Any says NO
                            Coordinator sends ROLLBACK
                            Participants undo changes
                            Release locks
                            
        Transfer ₹1000 from Account A to Account B
              Participants
                          Bank A DB
                          Bank B DB

              Flow
                  Prepare:
                         Bank A: Can debit ₹1000? → YES
                         Bank B: Can credit ₹1000? → YES
                  Commit:
                        Debit Account A
                        Credit Account B
                        
        ✅ Advantages of 2PC
               ✔️ Strong consistency
               ✔️ ACID compliance
               
        ❌ Disadvantages of 2PC
                ❌ Blocking protocol
                   If coordinator crashes → participants wait
                ❌ Poor scalability
                   Locks held for long time
      
 
 
  Transaction :
  ------------------------------------------------
  -> A transaction is sequency of action that must be executed step by step, if one step is fail the entire steps is must be roll back.
  -> A transaction has following the ACID properties.
     - Atomicity (All or Nothing) : 👉 A transaction is treated as one single unit.
                 Either all operations succeed
                 Or all operations fail and rollback
                 
                 Example
                         Money transfer ₹1000:
                         Debit from Account A ✅
                         Credit to Account B ❌ (fails)
                         ➡️ Rollback debit → no partial update
                         ✔️ No half-completed transactions
                         
     - Consistency (Data Must Follow Rules) : 👉 A transaction must move the database from one valid state to another.
                     All constraints, rules, triggers must be satisfied
                     No corruption of data
                     
                     Example
                             Account balance cannot be negative
                             Primary key must be unique
                             If a transaction violates rules → rollback
                             ✔️ Database integrity maintained
                             
                             
    - Isolation (Transactions Don’t Interfere) : 👉 Multiple transactions can run concurrently without affecting each other.
                                                 Each transaction behaves as if it is the only one running.
                                                 
    - Durability (Once Committed, Always Saved) : 👉 After a transaction commits, data will not be lost, even if:
                                                  System crashes
                                                  Power failure
                                                  Server restarts
                                                  
                                                  
  Transaction in Monolithic Vs Microservice
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  -> In monolithic applications, transactions are easy because all operations happen in a single database using ACID transactions.
     In microservices, transactions are distributed across services, so we use Saga pattern with compensating transactions instead 
     of traditional database transactions.
      
      Monolith → @Transactional
      Microservices → Saga
      Strong consistency → Monolith
      Scalability → Microservices
      
        
 17. Details of 3 Phase Commit
 ===============================================================================      
  -> 3PC is a distributed transaction protocol that improves Two-Phase Commit (2PC) by reducing blocking.
  -> 👉 It adds one extra phase so that participants don’t wait forever if the coordinator crashes.
  
  🤔 Why 3PC was introduced?
     Problem in 2PC
        . If Coordinator crashes after PREPARE
        . Participants wait forever
        . System gets blocked
        
      ➡️ 3PC solves this by adding a middle phase
      
  1️- Can-Commit Phase (Voting Phase)
        
     Coordinator asks:
                  “Are you able to commit?”
                  
    Participants:
                  Check resources
                  Reply YES or NO
                  
  2️- Pre-Commit Phase (Ready Phase)
  
     If all say YES:
                    Coordinator sends PRE-COMMIT
                    
     Participants:
                   Write transaction to log
                   Lock resources
                   Get ready to commit
                   
  3️- Do-Commit Phase (Final Commit)
  
     Coordinator sends COMMIT
     
     Participants:
                  Commit changes
                  Release locks
                  Send ACK
                  
                  
 Example: 
 
        Step-by-Step
        
                    Phase 1 – Can Commit?

                            A: Enough balance? → YES
                            B: Account valid? → YES

                    Phase 2 – Pre-Commit

                            Both lock accounts
                            Both write logs
                            Both ready to commit

                Phase 3 – Commit

                            Debit A
                            Credit B
                            Release locks
                  
                   ✔️ Transaction successful
                   
    💥 Failure Handling (Key Benefit)
                Coordinator crashes after Pre-Commit
                Participants know commit will happen
                They can commit on their own
                No indefinite waiting
                
   Three-Phase Commit is an extension of Two-Phase Commit that adds a pre-commit phase to avoid blocking when the coordinator fails.
   
   2PC → Prepare → Commit
   3PC → Can-Commit → Pre-Commit → Commit
   
   
18. What is Circuit Breaker Pattern?
 ====================================================================
 -> The Circuit Breaker pattern is used in microservices to prevent cascading failures.
    Cascading Failure - One failure causes multiple services to fail one after another
    👉 If one service is failing, we stop calling it for some time instead of retrying again and again.
    
    💻 Microservice Example (Simple)

              Services:
                       Order Service
                       Payment Service
                       
       Problem (Without Circuit Breaker)
                     Payment service is down ❌
                     Order service keeps calling it ❌
                     Threads get blocked
                     Whole system slows down ❌
        
       ✅ Solution: Circuit Breaker
                    Detect failures
                    Stop calling Payment Service
                    Return fallback response
                    Try again later
                    
       🔄 Circuit Breaker States
               1️- Closed (Normal State)
                       All requests go through
                       Failures are counted
                       
                       Request → Payment Service
                       
               2️- Open (Service is Broken)
                             Too many failures
                             Circuit opens
                             Requests fail immediately
                             
                       Request ✖ Payment Service
                       Response → Fallback
                       
               3️- Half-Open (Testing State)
                                  After wait time
                                  Send few test requests
                                  If success → Close
                                  If failure → Open again
                                  
   for Implement
   -----------------------
   we have to add dependency : resilience4j-spring-boot2
   configure in our properties file : 
                                     resilience4j:
                                        circuitbreaker:
                                               instances:
                                                   paymentService:
                                                   failure-rate-threshold: 50
                                                   minimum-number-of-calls: 5
                                                   wait-duration-in-open-state: 30s
                                                   permitted-number-of-calls-in-half-open-state: 2
                                                   sliding-window-size: 10
                                                   
     @CircuitBreaker(name = "paymentService", fallbackMethod = "paymentFallback")
     @GetMapping("/order")
     public String placeOrder() {
        return restTemplate.getForObject(
            "http://PAYMENT-SERVICE/pay",
            String.class
        );
    }

    public String paymentFallback(Exception e) {
        return "Payment service is currently unavailable. Please try later.";
    }
                                     
 
