 37. CQRS Design Pattern
 ================================================================================
 -> CQRS stands for Command Query Responsibility Segregation.
 
 🧠 What is CQRS?
   -: CQRS is a design pattern where you separate read operations (Queries) from write operations (Commands).
   -: CQRS separates read and write responsibilities into different models to improve scalability, performance, 
      and maintainability in complex systems.
     ( Scalability means: The ability of a system to handle more users, more data, or more load without breaking or slowing down.
                         “System grows smoothly when demand increases.”)
   Commands → change data
   Queries → read data          
            
    🔄 Traditional Approach (Without CQRS)
            Same model → Read + Write    
            Ex:  
                OrderService {
                      createOrder()
                      updateOrder()
                      getOrder()
                }
                
    ✅ CQRS Approach
           Command Model  → Create / Update / Delete
           Query Model    → Read / Fetch 
           
           Command side
               CreateOrderCommand
               UpdateOrderCommand
           Query side
               GetOrderQuery
               GetAllOrdersQuery
               
    🧪 Real-World Example 🛒 (E-commerce)

           Command side
                 Place Order
                 Cancel Order

           Query side
                View Orders
                Order History                     
            
  🔥 Why use CQRS?
     ✔ Better performance
     ✔ Independent scaling (read-heavy systems)
     ✔ Improves maintainability in complex systems
  
  ⚠️ When NOT to use CQRS?
     ❌ Simple CRUD applications
     ❌ Small systems
     ❌ When consistency complexity is not needed
           
 🧱 Step-by-Step CQRS Implementation
    We implemented CQRS by separating write APIs and read APIs, storing data in different models,
     and using events to keep the read model in sync.  
             
    🔹 Step 1: Split APIs (Command vs Query)
          Command APIs → change data
          Query APIs → read data      
           /api/commands/*
           /api/queries/*
             
    ✍️ Step 2: Command Side (WRITE)
         Command Object
         -----------------
            public class CreateOrderCommand {
                         private String orderId;
                         private BigDecimal amount;
            }
            
         Command Controller
         ---------------------
            @RestController
            @RequestMapping("/api/commands/orders")
            public class OrderCommandController {

              @PostMapping
              public ResponseEntity<String> createOrder(
                       @RequestBody CreateOrderCommand command) {

                 commandService.handle(command);
                 return ResponseEntity.ok("Order Created");
             }
          }
            
         Command Handler / Service          
        ------------------------------
        
          @Service
          public class OrderCommandService {

                 public void handle(CreateOrderCommand command) {
                 // validations
                 // business rules
                 // save to write DB
                     orderRepository.save(
                         new Order(command.getOrderId(), command.getAmount())
                     );

                 // publish event (important)
                     eventPublisher.publish(
                         new OrderCreatedEvent(command.getOrderId())
                    );
               }
            }
            
      📣 Step 3: Event (Bridge Between Write & Read)
      -----------------------------------------------------
         public class OrderCreatedEvent {
                       private String orderId;
         }
         
      Event can be sent using:
              Kafka
              RabbitMQ
              Spring Application Events (simple setup)
               
    Query Side (READ)
    ------------------------
      public class OrderView {
             private String orderId;
             private BigDecimal amount;
      }
              
    Event Listener (Updates Read DB)
    -------------------------------------
    
         @Service
         public class OrderEventHandler {

               @EventListener
               public void handle(OrderCreatedEvent event) {
                   orderViewRepository.save(
                         new OrderView(event.getOrderId(), BigDecimal.ZERO)
               );
            }
       }
                
    Query Controller
    ------------------------------
      @RestController
      @RequestMapping("/api/queries/orders")
      public class OrderQueryController {

             @GetMapping("/{id}")
             public OrderView getOrder(@PathVariable String id) {
                  return orderViewRepository.findById(id);
                 }
             }
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
 